SIMPLE: wrest
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Wrest
<hw>Wrest</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Wrested</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Wresting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>wresten</ets>, AS.
<ets>wr<?/stan</ets>; akin to <ets>wr<?/<?/</ets> a twisted band, and
<ets>wr⟦imac⟧<?/n</ets> to twist. See <er>Writhe</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To turn; to twist; esp., to twist or extort by
violence; to pull of force away by, or as if by, violent wringing or
twisting.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The secret <xex>wrested</xex> from me.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Milton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Our country's cause,⟦br⟧
That drew our swords, now secret <qex>wrests</qex> them from our
hand.</q> <rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They instantly <qex>wrested</qex> the government out of the hands
of Hastings.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To turn from truth; to twist from its natural or
proper use or meaning by violence; to pervert; to distort.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Wrest</qex> once the law to your authority.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Thou shalt not <qex>wrest</qex> the judgment of thy poor.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. xxiii. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Their arts of <qex>wresting</qex>, corrupting, and false
interpreting the holy text.</q> <rj><qau>South.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To tune with a wrest, or key.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Wrest
<hw>Wrest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of wresting; a
wrench; a violent twist; hence, distortion; perversion.</def>
<rj><au>Hooker.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Active or moving power.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A key to tune a stringed instrument of
music.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The minstrel . . . wore round his neck a silver chain, by which
hung the <qex>wrest</qex>, or key, with which he tuned his harp.</q>
<rj><qau>Sir W. Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A partition in a water wheel, by which the form of
the buckets is determined.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Wrest pin</b></col> <fld>(Piano Manuf.)</fld>, <cd>one of
the pins around which the ends of the wires are wound in a piano.</cd>
<au>Knight.</au> -- <col><b>Wrest plank</b></col> <fld>(Piano
Manuf.)</fld>, <cd>the part in which the wrest pins are
inserted.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Wrester</ent>⟦br⟧
